item.title: Pound Cake Serving and Preparation

item.content:encoded:

item.title: Cheesecake Serving and Preparation
item.dc:creator: websters_user
item.content:encoded:
Tools Needed to Prepare and Serve:

  • A long, non-serrated knife
  • A large plate or cutting board
  • A spatula or server

Thawing Options:

  • Microwave 1 or 2 slices at a time - Will be ready in under 30 seconds   OR
  • Thaw in refrigerator - Will be ready in 4-5 hours

Cutting and Serving Tips:

  • Place the cheesecake on a large plate or cutting board
  • Remove the lid from the pan and run the tip of a spatula between the frozen cheesecake and the side of the pan
  • Push the cheesecake up from the bottom to remove it. Slide the spatula under the cake and lift from the pan.
  • Before the first cut and in between cuts, dip the knife in warm water. Then, clean the knife with a paper towel between cuts.
  • Cut from the center, not all the way across the diameter of the cheesecake
  • After the cuts are complete, slide the spatula in to lift out each piece of cheesecake
  • Store any unused cheesecake in the refrigerator for up to 4 days

item.title: Cream Pie Serving and Preparation
item.dc:creator: websters_user
item.content:encoded:
Tools Needed to Prepare and Serve:

  • A long, non-serrated knife
  • A large plate or cutting board
  • A spatula or server

Thawing Options:

  • You can eat cream pies right from the freezer or thaw them in the refrigerator for a creamier texture
  • Individual pie slices will thaw faster than the whole pie

Cutting and Serving Tips:

  • Remove the pie from its packaging to slice
  • Remove the dome lid
  • Push the pie up from the bottom to lift it from the package
  • While frozen, cut your cream pie on a large plate or cutting board
  • Before the first cut and in between cuts, dip the knife in warm water. Then, clean it with a paper towel between cuts.
  • Cut from the center, not all the way across the diameter of the pie

Cutting and Serving Tips:

  • Cut the pie slice to the size of the server
  • Always cut from the center, not all the way across the diameter of the pie
  • Slowly draw the knife down to the bottom of the crust, stopping at the edge of the pan (do not cut through the end crust). Be careful not to drag too hard or you can cut through the foil pan and introduce foil to the pie slices.
  • For each piece, cut gently from the center twice to ensure you have a proper cut
  • Take the knife out and gently cut top-down through the crimp crust area (knife should be parallel with the table)
  • When you have both edges of the pie slice cut through, gently bend the crimped wall of the pan down (this gives a little more room to insert the pie server)
  • When inserting the pie server, remember the design of the pie tin:
  • Straight under crimp, angled down to the bottom, then straight across bottom
  • Lift up and you should have a clean-cut piece of pie
